<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nimbupani?a=R1LMx-7WAZk:fYGAUuVeSdQ:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nimbupani?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nimbupani?a=R1LMx-7WAZk:fYGAUuVeSdQ:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nimbupani?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\" border=\"0\"></img></a>
</div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/nimbupani/~4/R1LMx-7WAZk\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/nimbupani/~3/R1LMx-7WAZk/using-decimal-percentage-values-in-responsive-design.html" (20817 34128) old 1 nil nil ((title ((type . "html")) "Using decimal percentage values in responsive design") (link ((href . "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/nimbupani/~3/R1LMx-7WAZk/using-decimal-percentage-values-in-responsive-design.html"))) (updated nil "2013-03-26T04:24:00-07:00") (id nil "http://nimbupani.github.com/using-decimal-percentage-values-in-responsive-design") (content ((type . "html")) "<p>At work I get many samples of code to be reviewed, most of them with a warning &#8216;only works in Chrome&#8217;. Nevertheless, I open these pages in Safari &amp; mostly they work. Yesterday I came across something that didn&#8217;t. This post is a result of that investigation.</p>

