<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nimbupani?a=z9SMeMy1jgY:BQUyx0xqrjU:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nimbupani?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nimbupani?a=z9SMeMy1jgY:BQUyx0xqrjU:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/nimbupani?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\" border=\"0\"></img></a>
</div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/nimbupani/~4/z9SMeMy1jgY\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/nimbupani/~3/z9SMeMy1jgY/using-background-clip-for-text-with-css-fallback.html" (20749 37436) old 2 nil nil ((title ((type . "html")) "Using background clip for text with CSS fallback") (link ((href . "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/nimbupani/~3/z9SMeMy1jgY/using-background-clip-for-text-with-css-fallback.html"))) (updated nil "2013-02-02T14:25:00-08:00") (id nil "http://nimbupani.github.com/using-background-clip-for-text-with-css-fallback") (content ((type . "html")) "<p>I was looking at the lovely design of <a href=\"http://polygon.com\">polygon</a> when their use of <code>background-clip</code> &amp; <code>background: linear-gradient(…)</code> immediately suggested a JS-free fallback for using the non-standard <code>background-clip: text</code>.</p>

<h2>What it is</h2>

<p><code>background-clip</code> is a CSS property that was <a href=\"https://www.webkit.org/blog/164/background-clip-text/\">originally introduced in WebKit (in 2008)</a> that allows backgrounds specified on elements to clip to the text content of the element like so:</p>

<p><img src=\"http://s3.amazonaws.com/nimbublips/1359844612.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>

<p>by merely using the following code:</p>

<pre>body{
 color: transparent;
 background: url(path/to/bg/image) repeat;
